<li id="cite_note-Whitehead-2">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Whitehead_2-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Whitehead_2-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Whitehead_2-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFWhitehead1996">Whitehead, Kenneth (1996). <a href="http://www.ewtn.com/faith/teachings/churb3.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.ewtn.com/faith/teachings/churb3.htm" rel="nofollow">"How Did the Catholic Church Get Her Name?"</a>. Eternal Word Television Network<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.ewtn.com/faith/teachings/churb3.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.ewtn.com/faith/teachings/churb3.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.ewtn.com/faith/teachings/churb3.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 9 May 2008</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=How+Did+the+Catholic+Church+Get+Her+Name%3F&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Whitehead&amp;rft.aufirst=Kenneth&amp;rft.au=Whitehead%2C+Kenneth&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.pub=Eternal+Word+Television+Network&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ewtn.com%2Ffaith%2Fteachings%2Fchurb3.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Roman_Catholic_Church"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-McClintoc71-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-McClintoc71_3-0" title="">^</a></b> McClintock, p.&#160;71, quote: "The name may be found in a number of Roman Catholic writers, and is generally used in the constitution of those states in which the Roman Catholic Church is recognized as one of the recognized or tolerated State churches. It is, however, not the official name used by the authorities of the Church who rather dislike it, and substitute for it the name 'Catholic' or 'Holy Catholic' Church. The name 'Roman Church' is applied, in the language of the Church, to the Church or diocese of the Bishop of Rome."</li>
